{"abstract":[{"text":"Bridge the gap between tuples and ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collections","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Framework","title":"Tuplé","role":"collection","externalID":"Tuplé","modules":[{"name":"Tuplé"}],"symbolKind":"module"},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","text":"Overview","level":2,"anchor":"overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Despite tuples being very much like fixed-count arrays, they are not equipped with much of the built-in functionality that is provided for any type of collection in the standard library. ☹️","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This package addresses some of the omissions, bringing tuples and collections closer to feature parity."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"heading","text":"“Geneity”","level":4,"anchor":"Geneity"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Swift’s collections are homogeneous, meaning they’re generic over their "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collection\/element","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":". Some of what’s in this package does require the tuples you’re working with to be homogeneous, as well."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But it’s generally no more complex to support working with heterogeneous tuples, so this package defers to the choice of maximum versatility, supporting homogeneous tuples as a subset of heterogenous ones."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"For example, the code for reversing an ","type":"text"},{"code":"(Int, String)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":":","type":"text"}]},{"code":["reversed((1, \"Two\"))"],"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"…also supports ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"(Int, Int)"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["reversed((1, 2))"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Element-Count","level":4,"text":"Element Count"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This package will support arbitrary-count tuples, incorporating the evolution of ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/apple\/swift-evolution\/blob\/main\/proposals\/0393-parameter-packs.md"},{"text":", when possible.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Otherwise, the cap for support is tuples with "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"text":"4 elements","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":". This is the size limit found in 3D graphics frameworks such as "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/realitykit","isActive":true},{"text":" and libraries such as ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/spatial"},{"text":".  Supporting visionOS development by filling in tuple-shaped holes in that Apple-provided software is a primary motivator for this package, but it is otherwise unrelated to graphics.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"heading","level":5,"text":"Usage Examples","anchor":"Usage-Examples"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"You’ve got the source code here, so aside from reading this documentation, see the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Tests"},{"text":" folder for example usage! 😺","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[[]]},"topicSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Type-Aliases","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Properties","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tuple-\/Instance-Methods","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-\/Swift\/Sequence","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-\/Error"]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tup